---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { meta } from '../data/snapshot';
---
<Base
  title="Vision · CCIR"
  description="What a financialized compute market looks like — worked examples of deals settled on the CCIR reference rate, with CCIR as the neutral settlement index and nothing more."
  ogImage="/og/home.png"
  showTape={false}
>
  <section class="wrap top">
    <header class="page-head">
      <div class="kicker">Vision · What CCIR settles · {meta.as_of_date}</div>
      <h1>What a Financialized Compute Market Looks Like</h1>
      <p class="standfirst">
        The <a href="/research/unfinancialized-compute">research</a> prices what
        the missing market costs. This shows the deals that close the gap — cash
        settled on a neutral reference rate, with CCIR as the settlement index
        and nothing more.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="body">
      <p class="lead">
        Every worked example below is <strong>cash-settled</strong>: no GPUs
        change hands through the contract, and each party keeps buying or selling
        capacity physically as it does today. The contract references the
        <strong>CCIR reference rate</strong>, settled <strong>Asian-style</strong>
        — on the <em>average</em> of the daily rate over the term, not a single
        day's fix. Compute is consumed continuously, like power; an average
        matches the exposure and is far harder to move than one fixing. It is how
        power and commodity swaps already settle.
      </p>

      <!-- Example 1 -->
      <h2>1 · A lab and a cloud lock the price</h2>
      <p>
        An <strong>AI lab</strong> buying H100 capacity is exposed to prices
        <em>rising</em>; it wants to fix its cost to budget a training run. A
        <strong>neocloud</strong> selling that capacity is exposed to prices
        <em>falling</em>; it wants to fix revenue. They take opposite sides of one
        swap.
      </p>
      <div class="deal-wrap">
        <table class="data deal">
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="k">Notional</td><td>1,000 H100s × 1 year = 8.76M GPU-hours</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="k">Fixed strike (K)</td><td>$2.50 / GPU-hour</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="k">Floating</td><td>average CCIR H100 · Neocloud rate over the year (Ā)</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="k">Settlement</td><td>(Ā − K) × notional</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <ul class="outcomes">
        <li><strong>Ā = $3.00</strong> (prices rose): the cloud pays the lab (3.00−2.50) × 8.76M = <strong>$4.38M</strong>. The lab's physical bill rose, the hedge covered it — its all-in cost stays $2.50.</li>
        <li><strong>Ā = $2.00</strong> (prices fell): the lab pays the cloud <strong>$4.38M</strong>. The cloud's realized price fell, the hedge made it whole — its revenue is floored at $2.50.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Either way, both sides have certainty. Neither delivers compute through
        CCIR; they simply agree to settle against the rate CCIR publishes.
      </p>

      <!-- Example 2 -->
      <h2>2 · A cloud turns certainty into cheaper capital</h2>
      <p>
        A neocloud is building a cluster <em>ahead</em> of a signed offtake —
        merchant capacity, which is expensive to finance (uncontracted debt sizes
        at roughly half the advance and twice the coverage of contracted debt). It
        sells its output forward with the same swap: it receives fixed, pays
        floating, and its revenue is locked at K regardless of spot —
        <strong>synthetic cash-flow certainty</strong> without waiting for a
        signed customer.
      </p>
      <div class="deal-wrap">
        <table class="data deal">
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="k">Facility</td><td>$500M secured buildout loan</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="k">Hedge</td><td>revenue locked via a CCIR-settled swap</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="k">Lender response</td><td>more debt, tighter spread — the ~90bp cash-flow-certainty slice</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="k">Order of magnitude</td><td>~90bp on $500M ≈ <strong>$4.5M / year</strong>, plus a larger leverage lift</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        That ~90bp is the number the <a href="/research/unfinancialized-compute">research
        page</a> estimates the sector is paying today for the <em>absence</em> of
        this hedge. It is not a universal lever — a price hedge fixes revenue
        volatility, not the counterparty's credit, and lenders still size to
        collateral, sponsor and covenants. But where revenue volatility is the
        binding constraint, it moves the number.
      </p>

      <!-- Where it goes -->
      <h2>Where it goes next</h2>
      <p>
        Once a rate is stable enough to settle on, the rest of the structure
        follows the pattern power and freight already took. Dealers sell
        <strong>cluster swaps</strong> — swapping a specific fleet's settlement for
        the CCIR hub rate at a spread, and warehousing the basis. Buyers in one
        region hedge against the reference and lay off the <strong>locational
        basis</strong> separately. A forward curve lengthens as liquidity builds
        toward the tenor of the debt it supports. None of it requires CCIR to be
        more than the reference.
      </p>

      <h2>CCIR's role — and only role</h2>
      <p>
        In every case CCIR publishes the rate. It is <strong>not a counterparty,
        does not run a venue, holds no position, and marks nothing.</strong> It is
        the neutral settlement rate two sides agree to reference — the compute
        analog of a power hub index or SOFR. The parties, and their dealers, do
        everything else. That neutrality is the whole point: a price a market can
        settle on has to be one no participant controls.
      </p>

      <p class="method">
        Forward-looking. These structures do not exist in compute today; the page
        describes what a neutral reference makes possible, using the CCIR rate as
        the settlement index. Certainty premium (~90bp) from Gohdes/Simshauser/Wilson
        (2022, <em>Energy Economics</em>); see the
        <a href="/research/unfinancialized-compute">research</a> and the
        <a href="/credit">credit ledger</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>

  <style>
    .top { padding-top: 32px; }
    .page-head { max-width: 82ch; margin-bottom: 10px; }
    .page-head h1 {
      font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: var(--fs-3xl);
      line-height: var(--lh-display); font-weight: var(--weight-display);
      margin: 6px 0 12px;
    }
    .standfirst a { color: var(--accent); }
    .standfirst em { font-style: italic; color: var(--accent); }

    .body { max-width: 80ch; }
    .body .lead { font-size: var(--fs-lg); }
    .body h2 {
      font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: var(--fs-xl);
      margin: 30px 0 8px;
    }
    .body p { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: var(--fs-md); color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.65; margin: 0 0 14px; }
    .body p em { color: var(--accent); font-style: italic; }
    .body a { color: var(--accent); }

    .deal-wrap { border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-left: 2px solid var(--accent); background: var(--surface); margin: 8px 0 16px; overflow-x: auto; }
    table.deal { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; }
    table.deal td { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: var(--fs-sm); color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.5; vertical-align: top; }
    table.deal td.k {
      font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--fs-xs); color: var(--ink-dim);
      text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: var(--tracking-eye); white-space: nowrap;
      width: 30%; background: var(--surface-2);
    }
    table.deal td strong { color: var(--accent); }

    .outcomes { max-width: 84ch; margin: 4px 0 16px; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 8px; }
    .outcomes li { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: var(--fs-md); color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.6; }
    .outcomes strong { color: var(--ink); }

    .method {
      font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--fs-xs) !important;
      color: var(--ink-faint) !important; line-height: 1.7 !important;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); padding-top: 14px; margin-top: 26px !important; max-width: 90ch;
    }
    .method a { color: var(--accent); }
  </style>
</Base>
